WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.980 --> 00:00:03.904
Professor Ramamurti
Shankar: So,

00:00:03.904 --> 00:00:08.282
what did we do the last time?
Here is what we were talking

00:00:08.282 --> 00:00:12.065
about.
We were trying to describe an

00:00:12.065 --> 00:00:18.803
event as seen by two observers.
One will be called S and

00:00:18.803 --> 00:00:22.820
here is the x axis for
S;

00:00:22.820 --> 00:00:24.750
the other is called S
prime.

00:00:24.750 --> 00:00:29.120
S prime is sliding to
the right at velocity u.

00:00:29.120 --> 00:00:32.893
Therefore, at a certain
time--Let me say S is me

00:00:32.893 --> 00:00:35.984
and S prime is you.
When you pass me,

00:00:35.984 --> 00:00:39.920
I'm sitting at the origin of my
coordinates, x = 0.

00:00:39.920 --> 00:00:43.121
You're at the origin of your
moving coordinates,

00:00:43.121 --> 00:00:47.003
x prime = 0,
and when we crossed each other,

00:00:47.003 --> 00:00:50.000
that time we set as 0 in our
own clocks.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:55.413
We synchronized them so that
the event, x = 0,

00:00:55.413 --> 00:00:59.682
t = 0,
also had coordinate x

00:00:59.682 --> 00:01:04.680
prime = 0,
t prime = 0.

00:01:04.680 --> 00:01:07.809
When you and I crossed,
we pushed our stopwatches,

00:01:07.809 --> 00:01:10.938
we synchronized our clocks,
our origins coincided,

00:01:10.938 --> 00:01:15.248
and that's when it began.
So, after some time,

00:01:15.248 --> 00:01:18.717
you are here.
This is your frame and this is

00:01:18.717 --> 00:01:22.159
my frame.
If something happens here,

00:01:22.159 --> 00:01:28.413
something could be anything.
I hope you understand what an

00:01:28.413 --> 00:01:30.386
event is.
That's not a relativistic

00:01:30.386 --> 00:01:32.110
notion.
That's the very old notion.

00:01:32.110 --> 00:01:34.580
Something happens at some place;
firecracker goes off.

00:01:34.580 --> 00:01:38.860
I ask you, "When did it happen?"
and "Where did it happen?"

00:01:38.860 --> 00:01:41.340
and you are given the
coordinates.

00:01:41.340 --> 00:01:44.099
So, everything that happens is
an event.

00:01:44.099 --> 00:01:48.284
You saw Elvis,
I say, "Where did you see

00:01:48.284 --> 00:01:50.410
Elvis?"
At the supermarket.

00:01:50.410 --> 00:01:52.540
Okay.
When did you see Elvis?

00:01:52.540 --> 00:01:56.956
I would also ask you what you
were smoking because this third

00:01:56.956 --> 00:02:01.225
question, that's not an extra
coordinate but in this case I

00:02:01.225 --> 00:02:04.607
would like,
well, I should tell you beyond

00:02:04.607 --> 00:02:07.720
all the laughter that's a
serious issue.

00:02:07.720 --> 00:02:10.561
Why is that not a coordinate?
Why not ask more and more

00:02:10.561 --> 00:02:12.680
questions and call them all
coordinates?

00:02:12.680 --> 00:02:16.009
The reason the other things are
not coordinates is very

00:02:16.009 --> 00:02:19.055
important.
Why is time now suddenly a

00:02:19.055 --> 00:02:21.581
coordinate?
Well, as you could have always

00:02:21.581 --> 00:02:23.870
asked 100 years ago when did
something happen,

00:02:23.870 --> 00:02:28.988
and the reason is that you will
see in the new relativistic

00:02:28.988 --> 00:02:33.060
physics, x and t,
according to one person,

00:02:33.060 --> 00:02:35.816
get mixed up into x
prime and t prime of the

00:02:35.816 --> 00:02:38.435
other person.
The fact that space and time

00:02:38.435 --> 00:02:42.191
coordinates can be combined to
give the new space and time

00:02:42.191 --> 00:02:45.420
coordinates is why it‘s called
a coordinate.

00:02:45.420 --> 00:02:48.052
I'll say more about it later.
Now, by the way,

00:02:48.052 --> 00:02:52.904
I've posted some notes on this
topic for those of you who want

00:02:52.904 --> 00:02:57.182
to have a second pass at it.
I also don't know how much the

00:02:57.182 --> 00:03:00.686
textbook covers this topic
because I spend a lot of time on

00:03:00.686 --> 00:03:04.009
this topic, not in proportion to
what's in the book.

00:03:04.009 --> 00:03:07.259
So, you can look at those notes
which are posted today.

00:03:07.259 --> 00:03:11.305
Before all the Einstein stuff,
if something occurred here,

00:03:11.305 --> 00:03:14.924
you would say it's at a
distance x prime from

00:03:14.924 --> 00:03:17.638
your origin.
I will say it's at a distance

00:03:17.638 --> 00:03:20.929
x from my origin.
This difference between our

00:03:20.929 --> 00:03:25.635
origins would be ut.
Therefore, before Einstein,

00:03:25.635 --> 00:03:31.647
I would say x prime is
x - ut and you would say

00:03:31.647 --> 00:03:36.657
x should be what you
think is a coordinate +

00:03:36.657 --> 00:03:38.160
ut.

00:03:41.789 --> 00:03:44.659
This is just going back and
forth from you to me and you can

00:03:44.659 --> 00:03:47.479
already notice that to go back
and forth from you to me,

00:03:47.479 --> 00:03:50.238
we just change the sign of the
velocity, because I'm going to

00:03:50.238 --> 00:03:52.261
the right and you're going to
the left [Note:

00:03:52.261 --> 00:03:55.000
Left and right mixed up here.].
That's why the formulas have

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:58.300
sign of u reversed.
What is the big change after

00:03:58.300 --> 00:04:00.370
Einstein?
First is, I admit,

00:04:00.370 --> 00:04:04.426
the possibility that maybe you
will think the time elapsed

00:04:04.426 --> 00:04:08.979
since we synchronized our clocks
is not necessarily the same.

00:04:08.979 --> 00:04:12.292
I leave that option open that
t and t prime are

00:04:12.292 --> 00:04:14.887
not the same.
Second thing I do is--I have

00:04:14.887 --> 00:04:18.738
already explained to you that
the velocity of light coming out

00:04:18.738 --> 00:04:22.399
the same for different people is
very counterintuitive,

00:04:22.399 --> 00:04:25.227
because if you are going to the
right, I expect you to get a

00:04:25.227 --> 00:04:27.480
smaller speed and yet to get the
same answer.

00:04:27.480 --> 00:04:31.223
So, we know that it's because
we don't agree anymore on clocks

00:04:31.223 --> 00:04:34.486
and meter sticks being the same.
So in particular,

00:04:34.486 --> 00:04:37.323
you will say,
"I don't buy your prediction

00:04:37.323 --> 00:04:41.129
that I expect to get the answer
to be x - ut.

00:04:41.129 --> 00:04:43.595
I'm going to put a fudge
factor, gamma,

00:04:43.595 --> 00:04:46.710
which depends on the velocity
between you and me,

00:04:46.710 --> 00:04:49.629
because your lengths are not my
lengths."

00:04:49.629 --> 00:04:52.495
Likewise, I will tell you,
"I don't agree with your

00:04:52.495 --> 00:04:55.646
expectation that I should get
x prime + ut

00:04:55.646 --> 00:04:57.899
prime.
I don't believe your lengths

00:04:57.899 --> 00:05:00.959
are really my lengths,
but I'm going to put the same

00:05:00.959 --> 00:05:02.399
fudge factor,
gamma."

00:05:02.399 --> 00:05:04.889
This is a very interesting
result.

00:05:04.889 --> 00:05:08.735
If I think your meter sticks
are short so that I want to blow

00:05:08.735 --> 00:05:13.088
up the answer with some amount;
you are allowed to say the same

00:05:13.088 --> 00:05:15.256
about me.
It's one of the big paradoxes

00:05:15.256 --> 00:05:18.101
in relativity that we can accuse
each other of using meter

00:05:18.101 --> 00:05:19.379
sticks,
which are short,

00:05:19.379 --> 00:05:22.399
and we'll go into a little bit
more how that's even possible.

00:05:22.399 --> 00:05:26.292
But the postulates tell us that
if my fudge factor is gamma,

00:05:26.292 --> 00:05:28.800
yours should also be the same
gamma.

00:05:28.800 --> 00:05:33.423
So, gamma is what we don't know.
I showed you a trick to find

00:05:33.423 --> 00:05:36.027
gamma.
I said, let's imagine that this

00:05:36.027 --> 00:05:38.985
event here, which could've been
a firecracker,

00:05:38.985 --> 00:05:42.929
is triggered by a light pulse
that was emitted when you and I

00:05:42.929 --> 00:05:46.114
met here.
The light pulse goes racing and

00:05:46.114 --> 00:05:49.448
sets off an explosion here.
That's the event we are talking

00:05:49.448 --> 00:05:51.870
about.
That's not a generic event.

00:05:51.870 --> 00:05:55.035
It's a particular event in
which x has to be

00:05:55.035 --> 00:05:58.960
c times t because
that's the equation for a light

00:05:58.960 --> 00:06:03.093
pulse, according to me.
Light goes at the velocity of

00:06:03.093 --> 00:06:07.188
c, and the event has got
the same velocity,

00:06:07.188 --> 00:06:10.707
according to you.
This event here should be

00:06:10.707 --> 00:06:14.993
connected by a light pulse that
for x/t is c,

00:06:14.993 --> 00:06:19.279
and x prime/t
prime is the same c.

00:06:19.279 --> 00:06:21.925
Then, I said,
take these three equations,

00:06:21.925 --> 00:06:25.430
multiply the left-hand side by
the right-hand side,

00:06:25.430 --> 00:06:28.032
put in these numbers and
extract gamma,

00:06:28.032 --> 00:06:31.730
and I will not repeat that
part, and gamma was this.

00:06:36.839 --> 00:06:39.928
Once you've got this,
you can take this gamma and put

00:06:39.928 --> 00:06:42.370
it back here.
Let's see what we get.

00:06:42.370 --> 00:06:46.570
So I'm going to put what we get
here into this board.

00:06:46.570 --> 00:06:49.250
You guys got all of that?
Okay.

00:06:49.250 --> 00:06:52.204
So, I'm going to put it back
here, because this is just

00:06:52.204 --> 00:06:57.396
background from last lecture.
What we have then is x

00:06:57.396 --> 00:07:04.389
prime = x - ut divided by
this famous square root,

00:07:04.389 --> 00:07:08.500
and if you go and solve for
t prime in the other

00:07:08.500 --> 00:07:12.230
equation, it's a simple
algebraic manipulation,

00:07:12.230 --> 00:07:15.000
so I don't want to waste my
time doing that.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:21.838
You will find t prime
= t - ux/c^(2) divided by

00:07:21.838 --> 00:07:24.460
the same square root.

00:07:27.550 --> 00:07:30.332
These are priceless.
This is really all of

00:07:30.332 --> 00:07:33.854
relativity, all the funny stuff
you hear about E =

00:07:33.854 --> 00:07:36.970
Mc^(2), funny clocks,
the Twin Paradox.

00:07:36.970 --> 00:07:39.060
Everything comes from this
equation.

00:07:39.060 --> 00:07:42.597
And you people should be very
pleased that within,

00:07:42.597 --> 00:07:45.629
what, six weeks of starting
Physics 200,

00:07:45.629 --> 00:07:49.591
you have all the things you
need to understand these

00:07:49.591 --> 00:07:53.319
equations, to understand where
they came from.

00:07:53.319 --> 00:07:56.990
That's also the remarkable
thing about relativity.

00:07:56.990 --> 00:07:59.560
A lot of the modern things in
physics require a lot of

00:07:59.560 --> 00:08:01.832
mathematics.
In fact, if you want to take a

00:08:01.832 --> 00:08:04.963
beam and you want to load it
with weight and you want to see

00:08:04.963 --> 00:08:08.019
the stresses and strains,
the math in all that is 1,000

00:08:08.019 --> 00:08:11.319
times more difficult than this
one, and yet the mathematics of

00:08:11.319 --> 00:08:13.133
relativity is very,
very simple,

00:08:13.133 --> 00:08:16.045
and accessible to all of you,
and there is nothing that I

00:08:16.045 --> 00:08:18.800
know of that you don't know as
far as how to get these

00:08:18.800 --> 00:08:20.750
equations.
This is what you do.

00:08:20.750 --> 00:08:24.404
Everything follows from taking
these equations and analyzing

00:08:24.404 --> 00:08:27.501
them, extracting the
consequences and that's really

00:08:27.501 --> 00:08:31.155
more an issue of courage than
just intelligence because once

00:08:31.155 --> 00:08:34.683
you've got these equations,
you will have to take them,

00:08:34.683 --> 00:08:37.320
you'll have to follow them
where they take you.

00:08:37.320 --> 00:08:39.926
That's what we're going to do.
The rest of the whole remaining

00:08:39.926 --> 00:08:42.330
lecture, it's all about getting
information from these

00:08:42.330 --> 00:08:44.967
equations.
Now, some of you are not used

00:08:44.967 --> 00:08:47.293
to writing equations.
I've noticed,

00:08:47.293 --> 00:08:50.567
when you see something like
this, it's not clear what is

00:08:50.567 --> 00:08:53.261
being stated.
So, let me remind you one more

00:08:53.261 --> 00:08:55.750
time.
u is a fixed number.

00:08:55.750 --> 00:08:57.860
That's your speed relative to
mine.

00:08:57.860 --> 00:09:02.322
I see something happening,
I give it a pair of numbers,

00:09:02.322 --> 00:09:05.379
xt, you give the same
event,

00:09:05.379 --> 00:09:07.368
another pair of numbers,
x prime,

00:09:07.368 --> 00:09:09.072
t prime,
and this is how they are

00:09:09.072 --> 00:09:11.332
related.
So, I gave you an analogy,

00:09:11.332 --> 00:09:15.362
but let me repeat the analogy.
If you're now talking about the

00:09:15.362 --> 00:09:18.412
xy plane rather than the
xt plane,

00:09:18.412 --> 00:09:21.961
that guard is not an event.
That guard is a coordinate of a

00:09:21.961 --> 00:09:24.080
point, maybe where something is
sitting.

00:09:24.080 --> 00:09:27.899
I give to it a pair of numbers,
x and y.

00:09:27.899 --> 00:09:31.693
Now, you have a different
coordinate system,

00:09:31.693 --> 00:09:36.279
rotated relative to mine,
by some angle θ.

00:09:36.279 --> 00:09:39.378
To that same point,
same location,

00:09:39.378 --> 00:09:45.011
you measure x prime up
to here and t prime from

00:09:45.011 --> 00:09:49.850
there.
I'm sorry, x prime and

00:09:49.850 --> 00:09:55.632
y prime are measured
along your axis,

00:09:55.632 --> 00:10:03.164
and the formula there is
x prime = x cos θ + y

00:10:03.164 --> 00:10:12.039
sin θ and y prime is
-x sin θ + y cos θ.

00:10:12.039 --> 00:10:15.070
θ is the analog of the
velocity now.

00:10:15.070 --> 00:10:17.750
If θ is 0,
you and I agree completely.

00:10:17.750 --> 00:10:21.610
If θ is not 0,
your axis is rotated relative

00:10:21.610 --> 00:10:25.850
to mine, and the same point has
two different numbers,

00:10:25.850 --> 00:10:28.348
xy for me,
x prime/y prime

00:10:28.348 --> 00:10:31.009
for you, and the relation
between them is this.

00:10:31.009 --> 00:10:33.584
So, you plug in my x and
y, you can get your

00:10:33.584 --> 00:10:35.210
x prime and y
prime.

00:10:35.210 --> 00:10:40.898
Let me give a concrete example.
Let's take θ to

00:10:40.898 --> 00:10:44.348
π/4 or 45°.
Then, as you know,

00:10:44.348 --> 00:10:47.590
at 45, sine and cosine,
they're all the same.

00:10:47.590 --> 00:10:50.992
One over root 2.
So, in that case,

00:10:50.992 --> 00:10:56.993
x prime is x over
root 2 + y over root 2,

00:10:56.993 --> 00:11:03.191
and y prime is -x
over root 2 + y over root

00:11:03.191 --> 00:11:03.880
2.

00:11:09.450 --> 00:11:12.669
That's a special case when
θ is 45°.

00:11:12.669 --> 00:11:15.771
So, for every angle,
cosine and sine will reduce to

00:11:15.771 --> 00:11:18.997
usual simple numbers that happen
to be the [one over]

00:11:18.997 --> 00:11:21.834
square root of 2 here.
Then, it tells you my x

00:11:21.834 --> 00:11:24.243
and y are related to your
x prime and y

00:11:24.243 --> 00:11:26.080
prime in this manner,
and you can test it.

00:11:26.080 --> 00:11:30.682
For example,
take a point with coordinates

00:11:30.682 --> 00:11:33.559
(1,1).
(x,y) is 1,1.

00:11:33.559 --> 00:11:39.707
If (x,y) is (1,1),
and my axis is related to yours

00:11:39.707 --> 00:11:45.341
by 45°, (1,1) lies right there.
So, what I expect is your

00:11:45.341 --> 00:11:48.991
y prime, there's
no y prime,

00:11:48.991 --> 00:11:53.250
and the coordinate should be
entirely x prime.

00:11:53.250 --> 00:11:57.810
If I put in (1,1) and indeed
you find if I put x = y =

00:11:57.810 --> 00:12:02.439
1, y prime becomes 0.
And how about x

00:12:02.439 --> 00:12:05.990
prime? It becomes 1+1
over root 2;

00:12:05.990 --> 00:12:13.049
that means 2 over root 2 is the
square root of 2.

00:12:13.049 --> 00:12:16.429
The square root of 2,
of course, would be the lengthy

00:12:16.429 --> 00:12:20.200
measure this way because the
length of the vector is square

00:12:20.200 --> 00:12:22.103
root of 2,
and the vector is entirely

00:12:22.103 --> 00:12:25.370
along the x direction.
So, the length you will get for

00:12:25.370 --> 00:12:28.480
this coordinate will be root 2.
So, come back to these

00:12:28.480 --> 00:12:30.080
equations.
They're the same thing.

00:12:30.080 --> 00:12:33.980
If you want,
I can write x prime as

00:12:33.980 --> 00:12:39.402
x divided by this number
- u divided by this

00:12:39.402 --> 00:12:42.827
number times t.
So, you can think of 1 over

00:12:42.827 --> 00:12:46.243
this number here as the analog
of cos θ and

00:12:46.243 --> 00:12:49.299
u over this number as the
analog of sine.

00:12:49.299 --> 00:12:52.816
So, it's just that instead of
cosine and sine all being

00:12:52.816 --> 00:12:56.593
upstairs, some of the numbers
are down, some of the numbers

00:12:56.593 --> 00:12:58.763
are up.
But for a given u,

00:12:58.763 --> 00:13:01.960
these are also numbers constant
depending on u,

00:13:01.960 --> 00:13:04.200
and x prime is the
linear combination of x

00:13:04.200 --> 00:13:05.789
and t,
and t prime is some

00:13:05.789 --> 00:13:07.990
other linear combination of
x and t.

00:13:07.990 --> 00:13:11.809
But I should warn you that it
is not an ordinary rotation.

00:13:11.809 --> 00:13:14.988
In other words,
you cannot treat this as a

00:13:14.988 --> 00:13:19.199
cosine and that as a sine.
They're not cosine or sine of

00:13:19.199 --> 00:13:23.488
anything, because if they were,
this squared plus that squared

00:13:23.488 --> 00:13:26.160
should add up to 1,
and they won't.

00:13:26.160 --> 00:13:28.794
So, don't even try that.
This is not an ordinary

00:13:28.794 --> 00:13:31.629
rotation but it is still what
you can call a linear

00:13:31.629 --> 00:13:34.578
transformation.
Linear transformation means the

00:13:34.578 --> 00:13:38.560
new numbers are related to the
first powers of the old numbers.

00:13:38.560 --> 00:13:40.851
They are linear.
They don't involve t^(2)

00:13:40.851 --> 00:13:44.029
and x^(2).
Okay, so that is the content of

00:13:44.029 --> 00:13:48.176
the Lorentz transformation.
Everybody should understand

00:13:48.176 --> 00:13:51.370
what they do by way of going
back and forth.

00:13:51.370 --> 00:13:53.777
But now, you can go backwards.
You can say,

00:13:53.777 --> 00:13:57.766
"Well, how do I write x
in terms of x prime and

00:13:57.766 --> 00:14:02.201
t prime?"
There are two options open for

00:14:02.201 --> 00:14:04.537
you.
One is, these are simultaneous

00:14:04.537 --> 00:14:06.628
equations.
You've got to find a way to

00:14:06.628 --> 00:14:09.855
solve for x and t
in terms of x prime and

00:14:09.855 --> 00:14:12.659
t prime and all these
funny functions involving

00:14:12.659 --> 00:14:15.138
u.
You treat them all as constants

00:14:15.138 --> 00:14:17.380
and juggle them around,
multiply by this,

00:14:17.380 --> 00:14:19.759
divide by that,
but you shouldn't do that

00:14:19.759 --> 00:14:22.169
because you know what the answer
should be.

00:14:22.169 --> 00:14:26.133
The answer should be the same
as what I got with the velocity

00:14:26.133 --> 00:14:28.744
reversed.
So, x should be x

00:14:28.744 --> 00:14:31.419
prime + ut prime or the
square root.

00:14:31.419 --> 00:14:34.167
If I write the square root,
it means I don't feel like

